[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring bytecode manipulation**\n\nI'm considering adding JVM arguments for the build process, especially since there's mention of graalvmNative needing specific opens or exports. It looks like MethodHandles.privateLookupIn might work if the ObjectImporter package is open. I’m not sure if the unnamed module opens everything, but if it does, I can use privateLookupIn across classes in the same module.\n\nI also think about using Javassist for bytecode manipulation. There seems to be a catch with lookup.defineClass, and maybe I should handle potential errors. I'm wondering if it’s better to use raw hardcoded class file bytes, even if that feels a bit messy.\n\n**Considering bytecode generation**\n\nI see that adding coverage for ClassPool might not be a problem, but I need to focus on the active class only. Using Javassist to create a test helper seems too extensive. Perhaps manual bytecode generation would be better, so I’m thinking of writing a minimal class file generator with just JDK APIs.\n\nIt's quite a bit of code but won't pull in external libraries. I realize I may need to avoid naming conflicts if tests run repeatedly. Using a constant name could help here. I’ll also consider the class file version and constant pool entries while generating the bytecode.\n\n**Implementing dynamic class loading**\n\nI'm looking at using `MethodHandles.Lookup` to dynamically load the helper class with privateLookupIn. I see that I need to be cautious and catch any potential errors that might arise during this process. \n\nIf I call `Class.forName` on a helper class that's already defined, it will initialize that class in the JVM. That’s an important detail to keep in mind for managing class loading effectively—just need to make sure everything is neatly handled to avoid issues.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_057c0e17c89602810169f508207a4081a39f24124947ddde98